Further, solid-state 13C–NMR analysis (DMSO-d
                        6, 100 MHz, ppm) of f-CDs confirms the functionalization of CDs with EDTA (Fig. 3
                        ). The NMR spectrum demonstrates that d-CDs structure has commonly associated peaks with a carbon QDs structure such as carbon-aliphatic peaks at 72 and 45 ppm, confirming the formation of QDs architecture. The resonance peaks at 180 ppm correspond to sp2 bonded carbon atoms and subjected to carbonyl nuclei of the carboxylic acid group at the surface of f-CDs. Besides, the resonance peaks at 174.14 ppm are indicative of amide-carbonyl atoms which approve the functionalization of CDs with EDTA.
